chunks.text:
    Contents of the Partnership Deed
The Partnership Deed usually contains the following details :
• Names and Addresses of the firm and its main business ;
. Names and Addresses of all partners ;
. Amount of capital to be contributed by each partner ;
• The accounting period of the firm ;
• The date of commencement of partnership ;
. Rules regarding operation of Bank Accounts ;
• Profit and loss sharing ratio ;
• Rate of interest on capital , loan , drawings , etc ;
. Mode of auditor's appointment , if any ;
• Salaries , commission , etc , if payable to any partner ;
• The rights , duties and liabilities of each partner ;
. Treatment of loss arising out of insolvency of one or more partners ;
. Settlement of accounts on dissolution of the firm ;
. Method of settlement of disputes among the partners ;
• Rules to be followed in case of admission , retirement , death of a partner ; and
• Any other matter relating to the conduct of business .
Normally , the partnership deed covers all matters affecting relationship of
partners amongst themselves . However , if there is no express agreement on
certain matters , the provisions of the Indian Partnership Act , 1932 shall apply .

contents.text:
{
  "2024-25": "2024-25",
  "Accountancy - Partnership Accounts": "Accountancy - Partnership Accounts",
  "1.2.1 Provisions of Partnership Act Relevant for Accounting": "1.2.1 Provisions of the Partnership Act Relevant for Accounting",
  "The important provisions affecting partnership accounts are as follows:": "The important provisions affecting partnership accounts are as follows:",
  "Profit Sharing Ratio": {
    "description": "If the partnership deed is silent about the profit sharing ratio, the profits and losses of the firm are to be shared equally by partners, irrespective of their capital contribution in the firm."
  },
  "Interest on Capital": {
    "description": "No partner is entitled to claim any interest on the amount of capital contributed by him or her in the firm as a matter of right. However, interest can be allowed when it is expressly agreed to by the partners. Thus, no interest on capital is payable if the partnership deed is silent on the issue."
  },
  "Interest on Drawings": {
    "description": "No interest is to be charged on the drawings made by the partners if there is no mention in the Partnership Deed."
  },
  "Interest on Loan": {
    "description": "If any partner has advanced a loan to the firm for the purpose of business, he or she shall be entitled to receive interest on the loan amount at the rate of 6 percent per annum."
  },
  "Remuneration for Firm's Work": {
    "description": "No partner is entitled to receive a salary or other remuneration for taking part in the conduct of the business of the firm unless there is a provision for the same in the Partnership Deed."
  },
  "Apart from the above, the Indian Partnership Act specifies that subject to contract between the partners:": "Apart from the above, the Indian Partnership Act specifies that, subject to contract between the partners:",
  "If a partner derives any profit for him or herself from any transaction of the firm or from the use of the property or business connection of the firm or the firm name, he or she shall account for the profit and pay it to the firm.": "If a partner derives any profit for him or herself from any transaction of the firm or from the use of the property or business connection of the firm or the firm name, he or she shall account for the profit and pay it to the firm.",
  "If a partner carries on any business of the same nature as and competing with that of the firm, he or she shall account for and pay to the firm all profit made by him or her in that business.": "If a partner carries on any business of the same nature as and competing with that of the firm, he or she shall account for and pay to the firm all profit made by him or her in that business.",
  "Test your Understanding - I": "Test your Understanding - I",
  "1. Mohan and Shyam are partners in a firm. State whether the claim is valid if the partnership agreement is silent in the following matters:": "1. Mohan and Shyam are partners in a firm. State whether the claim is valid if the partnership agreement is silent in the following matters:",
  "(i) Mohan is an active partner. He wants a salary of Rs. 10,000 per year;": "(i) Mohan is an active partner. He wants a salary of Rs. 10,000 per year;",
  "(ii) Shyam had advanced a loan to the firm. He claims interest at 10% per annum;": "(ii) Shyam had advanced a loan to the firm. He claims interest at 10 percent per annum;"
}
{
  "text": "(iii) Mohan has contributed Rs. 20,000 and Shyam has contributed Rs. 50,000 as capital. Mohan wants an equal share in profits.\n(iv) Shyam wants interest on capital to be credited at a rate of 6% per annum.\n\n2. State whether the following statements are true or false:\n(i) A valid partnership can be formulated even without a written agreement between the partners;\n(ii) Each partner carrying on the business is both the principal and the agent for all the other partners;\n(iii) The maximum number of partners can be 50;\n(iv) Methods of settlement of disputes among the partners cannot be part of the partnership deed;\n(v) If the deed is silent, interest at the rate of 6% per annum would be charged on the drawings made by the partner;\n(vi) Interest on a partner's loan is to be given at a rate of 12% per annum if the deed is silent about the rate.\n\n2024-25\nAccounting for Partnership: Basic Concepts\n\n(v) If the deed is silent, interest at the rate of 6% per annum would be charged on the drawings made by the partner;\n(vi) Interest on a partner's loan is to be given at a rate of 12% per annum if the deed is silent about the rate.\n\n1.3 Special Aspects of Partnership Accounts\n\nThe accounting treatment for a partnership firm is similar to that of a sole proprietorship business, with the exception of the following aspects:\n• Maintenance of Partners' Capital Accounts;\n• Distribution of Profit and Loss among the partners;\n• Adjustments for Wrong Appropriation of Profits in the Past;\n• Reconstitution of the Partnership Firm; and\n• Dissolution of the Partnership Firm.\n\nThe first three aspects mentioned above have been taken up in the following sections of this chapter. The remaining aspects have been covered in the subsequent chapters.\n\n1.4 Maintenance of Capital Accounts of Partners",
  "notes": {
    "clarifications": [
      "Mohan and Shyam are partners in a business, with specified capital contributions and profit-sharing preferences.",
      "The statements listed are meant to assess understanding of partnership principles and legalities.",
      "The section on Special Aspects of Partnership Accounts outlines key differences in accounting for partnerships compared to sole proprietorships."
    ]
  }
}

