"Accounting_for_Partnership_Basic_Concepts": {
"1": "Discuss the main provisions of the Indian Partnership Act of 1932 that are relevant to partnership accounts if there is no partnership deed.",
"2": "Explain why it is considered better to make a partnership agreement in writing.",
"3": "Illustrate how interest on drawings will be calculated under various situations.",
"4": "How will you deal with a change in profit sharing ratio among existing partners? Take imaginary figures to illustrate your answer."
},
"Numerical_Questions": {
"1": {
"scenario": "Triphati and Chauhan are partners in a firm sharing profits and losses in the ratio of 3:2. Their capitals were Rs. 60,000 and Rs. 40,000 as on April 01, 2019. During the year, they earned a profit of Rs. 30,000. According to the partnership deed, both partners are entitled to Rs. 1,000 per month as salary and 5% per annum interest on their capital. They are also to be charged an interest of 5% per annum on their drawings, irrespective of the period, which is Rs. 12,000 for Tripathi and Rs. 8,000 for Chauhan. Prepare the partners' capital/current accounts when capitals are fixed.",
"Answer": {
"Tripathi_Current_Account_Balance": "Rs. 3,600",
"Chauhan_Current_Account_Balance": "Rs. 6,400",
"Tripathi_Capital": "Rs. 60,000",
"Chauhan_Capital": "Rs. 40,000"
}
},
"2": {
"scenario": "Anubha and Kajal are partners of a firm sharing profits and losses in the ratio of 2:1. Their capitals were Rs. 90,000 and Rs. 60,000. The profit during the year was Rs. 45,000. According to the partnership deed, both partners are allowed a salary of Rs. 700 per month to Anubha and Rs. 500 per month to Kajal. Interest is allowed on capital at 5% per annum. The drawings during the year were Rs. 8,500 for Anubha and Rs. 6,500 for Kajal. Interest is to be charged at 5% per annum on drawings. Prepare the partners' capital accounts, assuming that the capital accounts are fluctuating.",
"Answer": {
"Anubha_Capital_Account_Balance": "Rs. 1,09,860",
"Kajal_Capital_Account_Balance": "Rs. 70,140"
}
}
}
}
3. Harshad and Dhiman have been in partnership since April 01, 2019. No formal Partnership agreement was made. They contributed capital amounts of Rs. 4,00,000 and Rs. 1,00,000 respectively. In addition, Harshad advanced an amount of Rs. 1,00,000 to the firm on October 01, 2019. Due to a long illness, Harshad could not participate in business activities from August 1 to September 30, 2019. The profits for the year ended March 31, 2020, amounted to Rs. 1,80,000.

Harshad Claims:
(i) He should be given interest at the rate of 10% per annum on both his capital and loan;
(ii) Profits should be distributed in proportion to their capital contributions.

Dhiman Claims:
(i) Profits should be distributed equally;
(ii) He should be allowed Rs. 2,000 per month as remuneration for the period he managed the business in the absence of Harshad;
(iii) Interest on capital and loan should be allowed at the rate of 6% per annum.

