3. Harshad and Dhiman have been in partnership since April 01, 2019. No formal Partnership agreement was made. They contributed capital amounts of Rs. 4,00,000 and Rs. 1,00,000 respectively. In addition, Harshad advanced an amount of Rs. 1,00,000 to the firm on October 01, 2019. Due to a long illness, Harshad could not participate in business activities from August 1 to September 30, 2019. The profits for the year ended March 31, 2020, amounted to Rs. 1,80,000.

A dispute has arisen between Harshad and Dhiman.

Harshad Claims:
(i) He should be given interest at the rate of 10% per annum on both his capital and loan;
(ii) Profits should be distributed in proportion to their capital contributions.

Dhiman Claims:
(i) Profits should be distributed equally;
(ii) He should be allowed Rs. 2,000 per month as remuneration for the period he managed the business in the absence of Harshad;
(iii) Interest on capital and loan should be allowed at the rate of 6% per annum.

You are required to settle the dispute between Harshad and Dhiman. Additionally, prepare the Profit and Loss Appropriation Account.

(Answer: Harshad's share in profit is Rs. 88,500, and Dhiman's share in profit is Rs. 88,500.)
4. Aakriti and Bindu entered into a partnership for making garments on April 01, 2019, without any formal Partnership Agreement. They introduced capitals of Rs. 500,000 and Rs. 300,000 respectively on October 01, 2019. Aakriti advanced Rs. 20,000 by way of a loan to the firm without any agreement regarding interest. The Profit and Loss Account for the year ended March 31, 2020, showed a profit of Rs. 43,000. The partners could not agree upon the question of interest and the basis of division of profit. You are required to divide the profits between them by preparing a Profit and Loss Appropriation Account. Also, provide reasons in support of your answer.  
(Answer: Profit is shared equally between Aakriti and Bindu, resulting in Rs. 21,200 each.)

5. Rakhi and Shikha are partners in a firm, with capitals of Rs. 200,000 and Rs. 300,000 respectively. The profit of the firm for the year ended 2016-17 is Rs. 23,200. As per the Partnership Agreement, they share the profit in their capital ratio, after allowing a salary of Rs. 5,000 per month to Shikha and interest on partners' capital at the rate of 10% per annum. During the year, Rakhi withdrew Rs. 7,000 and Shikha withdrew Rs. 10,000 for their personal use. As per the partnership deed, salary and interest on capital appropriation are treated as charges on profit. You are required to prepare a Profit and Loss Appropriation Account and Partners' Capital Accounts.  
(Answer: Loss transferred to Rakhi's Capital is Rs. 34,720 and Shikha's Capital is Rs. 52,080.)

6. Lokesh and Azad are partners sharing profits in the ratio of 3:2, with capitals of Rs. 50,000 and Rs. 30,000, respectively. Interest on capital is agreed to be paid at the rate of 6% per annum. Azad is allowed a salary of Rs. 2,500 per annum. During 2016, the profits prior to the calculation of interest on capital but after charging Azad's salary amounted to Rs. 12,500. A provision of 5% of profits is to be made in respect of the manager's commission. Prepare the Partners' Capital Accounts and the Profit and Loss Appropriation Account.

