chunks.suggestedText:
{
  "Accounting for Partnership: Basic Concepts": {
    "1. Definition of Partnership": "A partnership is defined as a relationship between two or more persons who agree to share profits and losses from a business. If some persons join hands for the purpose of some charitable activity, it will not be termed as a partnership.",

    "2. Liability of Partners": "Each partner is liable jointly with all the other partners and also severally to third parties for all the acts of the firm done while he is a partner. Not only that, the liability of a partner for acts of the firm is also unlimited. This implies that his private assets can also be used for paying off the firm's debts.",

    "3. Partnership Deed": {
      "3.1 Definition": "A partnership comes into existence as a result of an agreement among the partners. The agreement can be either oral or written. The Partnership Act does not require that the agreement must be in writing. However, wherever it is in writing, the document that contains the terms of the agreement is called a 'Partnership Deed'.",

      "3.2 Contents": "The Partnership Deed generally contains details about all aspects affecting the relationship between the partners, including the objective of the business, contribution of capital by each partner, the ratio in which the profits and losses will be shared by the partners, and the entitlement of partners to interest on capital, interest on loans, etc.",

      "3.3 Alterations": "The clauses of the Partnership Deed can be altered with the consent of all the partners. The deed should be properly drafted and prepared as per the provisions of the 'Stamp Act' and preferably registered with the Registrar of Firms."
    }
  }
}

