chunks.suggestedText:
{"table_title":"Distinction between Fixed and Fluctuating Capital Accounts","keywords":"fixed capital, fluctuating capital, accounting principles, partnership accounting","summary":"The following table contains the main points of differences between fixed and fluctuating capital methods in partnership accounting. It highlights distinctions such as the number of accounts maintained, items related to the partnership deed, the nature of fixed balances, and the credit balance status.","trends":"N/A"}
{"basis_of_distinction":"Number of accounts","fixed_capital":"Under this method, two separate accounts are maintained for each partner viz., 'capital account' and 'current account'.","fluctuating_capital":"Each partner has one account, i.e., capital account, under this method."}
{"basis_of_distinction":"Items related to deed","fixed_capital":"Drawings, salary, interest on capital, etc. are posted (transferred) in the current accounts and not in the capital accounts.","fluctuating_capital":"All adjustments for drawings, salary, interest on capital, etc., are posted (transferred) in the capital accounts."}
{"basis_of_distinction":"Fixed balance","fixed_capital":"The capital account balance remains unchanged unless there is addition to or withdrawal of capital.","fluctuating_capital":"The balance of the capital account fluctuates from year to year."}
{"basis_of_distinction":"Credit balance","fixed_capital":"The capital accounts always show a credit balance.","fluctuating_capital":"The capital account may sometimes show a debit balance."}

The table outlines the differences between fixed and fluctuating capital accounts in partnership accounting. It specifies that under the fixed capital method, each partner maintains two separate accounts: a capital account and a current account, whereas under the fluctuating capital method, each partner has only one capital account. It also explains that in the fixed capital method, items like drawings and interest are posted in current accounts, while in the fluctuating method, they are posted in capital accounts. The fixed capital method keeps the capital account balance unchanged unless there is a change in capital, while the fluctuating method allows the balance to change annually. Additionally, fixed capital accounts always show a credit balance, whereas fluctuating capital accounts may sometimes show a debit balance.

