{"table_title":"Statement Showing Net Effect of Omitting Interest on Capital","keywords":"Rameez, Zaheer, interest on capital, partnership accounting","summary":"The following table contains the net effect of omitting interest on capital for partners Rameez and Zaheer. It details the amounts that should have been credited as interest, the amounts actually credited, and the resulting differences. Rameez has an excess credit, while Zaheer has a shortfall."}
{"Details":"(i) Amount which should have been credited as interest on capital","Rameez (Rs.)":"3,000 (Cr.)","Zaheer (Rs.)":"6,000 (Cr.)"}
{"Details":"(ii) Amount actually credited by way of share of profit (Rs. 9,000 divided equally)","Rameez (Rs.)":"4,500 (Dr.)","Zaheer (Rs.)":"4,500 (Dr.)"}
{"Details":"(iii) Difference between (i) and (ii) (Net effect)","Rameez (Rs.)":"Dr. 1,500 (Excess)","Zaheer (Rs.)":"Cr. 1,500 (Short)"}

The table titled "Statement Showing Net Effect of Omitting Interest on Capital" outlines the financial adjustments needed due to the omission of interest on capital for partners Rameez and Zaheer. It specifies the amount that should have been credited as interest on capital, which is 3,000 (Cr.) for Rameez and 6,000 (Cr.) for Zaheer. The actual amount credited by way of share of profit is 4,500 (Dr.) for both partners. The net effect shows that Rameez has an excess credit of 1,500, while Zaheer's account is short by the same amount.

